THE FEAST OF FOOLS - CORRECTED EDITION
Adventure Profile
Title: The Feast of Fools
 Location: Falkreath Hold (Lakeview Manor & Surrounding Wilds)
 Party: 4–5 Players (Adept Tier / 4 AP)
 Time: 2–3 Hours

PART 1: THE ROAD TO LAKEVIEW
Time: Late Afternoon
Setting the Scene
(Read Aloud)
"The road to Falkreath has changed in recent weeks. The air, usually thick with the scent of fresh-cut pine and sawdust, now smells of damp rot and old woodsmoke. You pass Half-Moon Mill, and the wheel stands still, the water rushing past it without purpose. The lumber industry—the heartbeat of this hold—has suffered a stroke.
You are a team of specialists. Professionals with scars to prove it. You have been summoned by letter to Lakeview Manor, a construction site nestled in the northern cliffs, by a man named Thane Valmir.
The letter promised two things that are increasingly rare in Skyrim: A massive sum of gold and 'A task suited for those with a refined palette for danger.'
As your wagon creaks up the winding mountain path, leaving the gloomy fog of the town behind, you break through the tree line. The sun is setting, painting the sky in bruises of purple and gold. Ahead, you see the skeleton of a massive house rising from the rock—Lakeview Manor. It is half-finished, surrounded by scaffolding, yet lights blaze from the completed Great Hall, and you can hear the faint, incongruous sound of a string quartet playing over the wind."
The "Establishment" Phase
The Situation: The wagon rumbles steadily uphill. In the center of the cart sits a small, heavy crate stamped with Thane Valmir's wax seal. It is labeled: "Advance Payment. Handle with Care."
The crate is secured shut, but you can hear the faint, liquid sloshing of something valuable inside. It has a sliding panel on the side rather than a hinged lid.
GM to Players: "You have the letter, the map, and this crate. The road is getting rougher as you climb. Do you inspect the payment now, or leave it sealed until you arrive?"
(If a player chooses to slide the panel open):
The Complication: Just as the panel slides back, the wagon's wheel slams into a deep pothole. The cart lurches violently to the left.
The contents—a bottle of Honningbrew Gold Reserve, glowing amber in the sunset light—slides out of the side opening, slick glass moving fast towards the gap in the floorboards.
GM to Players: "Gravity has taken hold of your advance. Who is closest, and what are you doing?"
Resolution: The Bottle
If Caught/Saved: You secure the bottle. The cork holds. You have preserved 500 gold septims worth of wine—or a very expensive drink for later.
If Dropped/Shattered: The bottle smashes against the floorboards. The cart fills with the smell of rich, fruity vintage. The driver groans. "Well, that's coming out of my pay." (Valmir will sniff the air when you arrive and look disappointed).
Transition: "With the immediate crisis of the wine resolved (one way or another), the wagon crests the final hill. The estate looms ahead."

PART 2: THE HOST AND THE HUNGER
Time: Sunset - 1 Hour
The Arrival
(Read Aloud)
"The wagon rolls through the open gates of the estate. The courtyard is a chaotic blend of construction site and ballroom. Scaffolding hugs the stone walls, but the mud has been covered with expensive rugs. Tables are being set with crystal goblets by terrified servants.
In the center of the chaos stands Thane Valmir. He is a High Elf dressed in an outfit that costs more than a village—crimson velvet, gold threading, and a ridiculous feathered cap. But what catches your eye is the pin on his lapel: the golden wings of the Aldmeri Dominion, the Thalmor.
He is currently screaming at a Nord foreman.
'I don't care about load-bearing walls! I care about the sightlines! If First Emissary Elenwen cannot see the sunset from the head table, I will have you building latrines in Hammerfell!'"
The Proposition
(Valmir spots the party. His expression shifts instantly from rage to delight. He spreads his arms wide, ignoring the mud splattering his boots.)
Valmir: (He dismisses the foreman with a wave and approaches you)
"'Ah! The talent! You look... wonderfully rugged. Look at those scars! That grit! You reek of capability and violence. Perfect.'"
(his voice dropping to a conspiratorial whisper.)
"'You received my letter? Good. Now, listen closely. This party is a diplomatic necessity. The Jarl will be here. General Tullius's staff will be here. And, most importantly, the Thalmor High Command will be in attendance. We are going to drink, laugh, and show them that Skyrim is perfectly civilized.'"
(He wipes a bead of sweat from his forehead. The fear in his eyes is real.)
"'But I have a disaster. My couriers are incompetent. Or dead. It doesn't matter. Three essential components of tonight's feast are missing. If I serve stale bread to a Justiciar… I need you to save my party/life.'"
The Menu
(He produces a piece of thick parchment, written in elegant calligraphy. He thrusts it into your hands.)
GM: Hand the players the "Shopping List" (physically or digitally).
THE MISSING COURSES
The Vintage: One crate of Surilie Brothers 3E 433.


Location: Pinewatch. (Lore: A cabin that fronts a massive bandit sanctuary).
Valmir's Delusion: "My courier has decided to take an unauthorized break at Pinewatch. He has been stationary at that cabin for three hours. He is undoubtedly drinking my stock with the woodsman who lives there. Go fire him and bring me the crate."
The Reality: Pinewatch is a front for a bandit operation. The courier didn't stop for a drink; he was waylaid. The "woodsman" is a lookout for a much larger, dangerous crew in the cellars.
The Entertainment: "Buttercup" the Pyro-Goat.


Location: Greywater Grotto.
Valmir's Delusion: "The beast handler I hired said the creature was 'spirited' and ran into a cave. He's refusing to go in after it. Laziness!"
The Reality: The handler is refusing because Greywater Grotto is a predator's den (Valerius's leftover vampires). The goat didn't just wander in; it was likely lured or chased, and now the predators are dealing with a goat that breathes fire.
The Centerpiece: Grand Champion Mammoth Cheese.


Location: Secunda's Kiss. (Giant Camp).
Valmir's Delusion: "I sent a team of 'Cultural Liaisons' with a chest of gold to purchase the cheese directly from the source. They haven't reported back. The Giants are probably just haggling."
The Reality: You cannot buy cheese from Giants. The "Liaisons" are dead. The Giants likely viewed the intrusion as an attack. The cheese is there, but the "transaction" was a massacre.
The Deadline
(Valmir checks a jeweled pocket watch.)
Valmir: "'The guests arrive in three hours. I don't care how you get these things. Bribe the bandits, wrestle the goat, murder the giants. Just get them here before the first toast. 600 gold for each of you if the table is full by sundown.'"
(He turns back to the foreman, screeching.)
"'And move that wall! The Dominion does not look at unfinished brickwork!'"
The Choice
GM to Players: "You have the list. You have the map. You know who is coming to dinner. The sun is already dipping lower. Which disaster do you tackle first: The Wine, The Goat, or The Cheese?"

OBJECTIVE A: THE VINTAGE
Location: The Crossroads near Pinewatch
 Time: Sunset - 45 Minutes
The Scene
(Read Aloud)
"You follow the courier's route down the winding road from the Manor. It doesn't take long to find the 'rest stop' Valmir described.
Near the innocuous-looking cabin of Pinewatch, a fine carriage lies overturned in the ditch. The horse is gone— cut loose or eaten. The driver, Valmir's courier, is slumped against the wheel, a nasty bruise on his head, unconscious but breathing.
Standing over the wreckage are five men. They aren't wearing bandit leather or Stormcloak blue; they are wearing sawdust-stained tunics and heavy work gloves. These are former mill workers.
They are currently taking turns on the reinforced wine crate with a woodcutter's axe, trying to pry it open without smashing the bottles inside.
Their leader, a burly Nord swaying slightly on his feet, raises a bottle he's already managed to liberate. He spots you and points the axe unsteadily.
'Oi! Keep walking! This is... hic... severance pay!'"
The Opposition
"Tipsy" Torbjorn & The Mill Crew
Identity: Former workers from Half-Moon Mill. When Hert died (or vanished) and the mill closed, they weren't paid. They are starving, drunk on the first bottle, and desperate.
The Vibe: Tragic Comedy. They are holding 500 gold septims worth of wine, but they would trade it all for a venison stew.
The Encounter ME AVA KANA ZACH
The players need the crate. Torbjorn thinks it's his ticket to survival.
Valmir's Orders: "Fire the courier."
The Reality: The courier was knocked out. The "bandits" are just hungry locals.
Approach A: The Diplomat (Social)
If the players try to talk, Torbjorn is belligerent but listening.
Torbjorn: "The Mill closed! The Jarl's building a palace while we eat bark! This wine... we sell this, we eat for a year. You want it? You pay us."
The Trade: They will accept 50 Gold or 5 Rations (food) in exchange for the crate. They don't actually want the wine; they want what it can buy.
The Intimidation: (Standard Guile Check). "We are armed professionals. You are drunk woodcutters holding axes. Walk away."
Success: They drop the axe and run.
Failure: Torbjorn roars, "I'd rather die fighting than starving!" (Combat begins).
Approach B: The Cleaner (Combat)
If the players attack or fail the social check, the laborers fight.
Enemies:
1x Torbjorn (Adept Tier, TL 1 Brute - High HP, drunk).
4x Desperate Laborers (Minion - 1 HP).
Mechanic: Sloppy Fighting. The laborers have Disadvantage on all attacks because they are drunk. However, they are unpredictable—on a Critical Success (Nat 1 by players or Nat 20 by enemies), a laborer accidentally throws a wine bottle (Improvised Weapon, 2 Dmg).
Resolution
Once the laborers are dealt with (paid off, scared off, or killed):
The Courier: He wakes up groggy. "Did I... did I deliver it? The Thane gets so angry when the corks are dry." He flees back to Solitude if released.
The Loot:
The Crate: Contains 11 bottles of Surilie Brothers 3E 433 (Valmir won't notice one is missing/drunk by Torbjorn).
Torbjorn's Necklace: Around the leader's neck is a heavy iron medallion.
Item: The Laborer's Amulet (Effect: Fortify Stamina/FP +10).
Transition: "You have the vintage. The sun is sinking lower. Two disasters remain."

OBJECTIVE B: THE PYRO-GOAT
Location: Greywater Grotto
 Time: Sunset - 30 Minutes
The Scene
(Read Aloud)
"The path to Greywater Grotto is marked by scorched grass and the distinct smell of singed fur. The cave entrance is dark, damp, and echoes with strange sounds: the hiss of pain, the splash of water, and the demonic bleating of a farm animal.
You step inside the cavern. The main chamber is dominated by a pool of stagnant water and a central rock island.
On that island stands Buttercup. The goat looks perfectly normal, except for its glowing red eyes and the fact that it is currently hovering two feet off the ground.
Surrounding the island are four vampires—the leftovers of Valerius's court. Two of them are Feral, snarling beasts who have lost their minds to hunger. They keep lunging at the goat, trying to grapple it.
As you watch, Buttercup opens its mouth. 'BAAAA-FWOOSH!'
A cone of magical fire erupts from the goat's mouth. The Feral vampires scream as their skin blisters, diving into the water to put themselves out.
Hiding behind a stalagmite near the entrance are the other two vampires—Cognizant Fledglings. One of them has his head in his hands. 'It burned me again,' he whimpers. 'Why won't it just let us eat it?'"
The Encounter
State: Chaotic Stalemate.
The Ferals are distracted by the goat. The Fledglings are distracted by their misery. The Goat hates everyone.
The Timer:
At the end of every round (Initiative count 0), Buttercup bleats.
Effect: 15-foot Cone of Fire.
Damage: 4 Fire Damage (Agility Save for half).
Direction: Random (Roll d4: 1=North, 2=South, 3=East, 4=West).
The Opposition: Valerius's Rejects
2x Feral Vampires (Stage 5 - Mindless).
HP: 25 (Regenerating).
Tactic: They ignore the players until attacked. They are obsessed with the goat. If the goat burns them, they take Double Damage (Fire Weakness).
2x Cognizant Fledglings (Stage 3 - Desperate).
HP: 20.
Tactic: They are hiding. If they see the players, they do not attack immediately.
Player Approaches
Approach A: The Bargain (Social)
If the players speak to the cowering Fledglings instead of attacking.
Fledgling Dialogue: "We just wanted a snack! Valerius left us here with nothing! No blood, no instructions, just hunger."
The Deal: "Take it! Please! Just take the daemon-goat away so the Ferals will calm down and we can hunt something normal. We won't stop you."
Result: The Fledglings retreat into the shadows. The players only have to deal with the Ferals (who are too stupid to negotiate) and the Goat.
Approach B: The Cleanse (Combat)
If the players attack, or the Ferals turn on them.
The Hazard: The vampires are weak to fire. The players can try to shove the vampires into the path of the goat's breath for massive damage.
The Water: Pushing a vampire into the deep water pool prevents them from regenerating for 1 round.
The Catch: Wrangling Buttercup
Once the vampires are dead or gone, the party must secure the package.
The Problem: Buttercup is aggressive.
Solution 1 (The Rodeo): A player must succeed on a Grapple (Might) or Agility check to grab the goat.
Complication: On a failure, the goat uses Levitate to hop 15 feet into the air, forcing the player to climb or jump to catch it.
Solution 2 (Feed It): A Guile (Animal Handling) check with food (an apple or carrot) calms the goat down long enough to tie a rope around it.
Resolution
The Fledglings: If spared, they slink away, promising to go south to Cyrodiil and never return. If killed, they turn to ash.
Loot:
Ash Pile (Fledgling): Finds a gold ring with a ruby setting.


Item: Ring of the Hearth (Effect: Resist Fire +20%).
The Goat: Buttercup is secured. (Note: The goat gives +1 Morale to the party because it is cute when not breathing fire).


Transition: "You have the vintage and the goat. The sun is dangerously low. Only the centerpiece remains."

OBJECTIVE C: THE CHEESE
Location: Secunda's Kiss (Giant Camp)
 Time: Sunset - 15 Minutes
The Scene
(Read Aloud)
"You crest the ridge overlooking the basin of Secunda's Kiss. The air shakes with the sound of impact—massive clubs hitting the earth, the trumpeting of panicked mammoths, and the screams of men dying badly.
Thane Valmir's 'Cultural Liaisons' are long dead; you can see their crushed bodies pressed into the mud near the central campfire, a shattered chest of gold glittering uselessly beside them. But the violence hasn't stopped.
A crew of Mammoth Poachers is scattered along the high ridges, firing arrows down into the pit. Two Giants are in a rage, swinging tree-trunk clubs blindly at the annoyances on the cliffs, while their Mammoths stampede back and forth in a panic.
In the center of this chaos, sitting serenely on a ceremonial stone shelf fifteen feet up, is the prize: The Grand Champion Cheese. A wheel of yellow gold the size of a wagon wheel, wrapped in mammoth leather.
It is 200 pounds of dairy. It is unguarded. It is also directly in the crossfire."
The Heist Mechanics
This is not a stand-up fight; it is an infiltration into an active warzone.
The "Giant" Rule (Environmental Hazard):
The Giants are Adept Tier TL 3 threats, far above the party's pay grade. They are treated as lethal hazards.
Trigger: If a player fails a Stealth check within 30 feet of a Giant, or attacks a Giant/Mammoth directly.
The Attack: The Giant uses a Reaction to make a Club Slam attack (+10 to hit).
The Consequence: On a hit, the player takes 40 Bludgeoning Damage and is launched 100 feet into the air. This is effectively an instant kill or removal from the encounter.
Phase 1: The Approach
The party must cross the basin floor to reach the back wall without drawing the ire of the Giants or the Poachers.
Distance: 60 feet of mud and angry wildlife.
The Stampede (Hazard): At the start of every round, the Mammoths charge across the field.
Avoidance: Players must make a Standard Agility (Stealth) or Athletics check to navigate the mud and avoid the stomping beasts.
Failure: The character is clipped by a mammoth. Take 8 Crushing Damage and fall Prone in the mud.
Poacher Fire: The Poachers are focused on the Giants, but a Critical Failure on a Stealth check draws a stray arrow (4 Damage).
Phase 2: The Lift
The Cheese is on a ledge 15 feet up.
Getting Up: Requires a Standard Agility (Climbing) check or a boost from an ally.
Getting Down: The Cheese weighs 200 lbs.
Controlled Descent: Requires a Hard (-2) Might check to lower it without dropping it.
The Drop: If failed, the cheese falls with a loud THUD. This noise alerts the Poacher Captain on the ridge.
Phase 3: The Interception
As soon as the Cheese touches the ground, a shout echoes from the high ridge.
Poacher Captain: "Forget the tusks! They're stealing the winter reserve! Drop them!"
The Poachers shift fire from the Giants to the Party. The Party must escape the basin while carrying the loot.
Enemy Stat Blocks
Poacher Captain
Archetype: Adept Tier, Threat Level 2 Skirmisher (Sniper)
Stats: Agility 17, Guile 14, Might 12, Magic 8.
HP: 35.
DR: 4 (Hide Armor + Position).
Weapon: Dwarven Bow of Storms (10 Damage + 5 Shock Damage + 5 FP Drain).
Position: He stays on the High Ridge (60 feet away, +2 DR from Cover).
Ability: Pinning Shot. If his attack hits, the target must make a Might Save or be Immobilized (Movement 0) for 1 turn (pinned by the arrow or shock muscle spasm).
Tactics: He targets whoever is carrying the Cheese to slow them down.
Poacher Sharpshooters (x2)
Archetype: Adept Tier, Threat Level 1 Minion
Stats: Agility 15, Might 10, Magic 6, Guile 10.
HP: 15 each.
DR: 2 (Leather Armor).
Weapon: Hunting Bow (6 Damage).
Tactics: They fire volleys into the mud to herd the players toward the Giants.
The "Cheese Bowling" Mechanic
The cheese is too heavy to run with (Half Speed). However, it is round.
Action: As a Major Action, a player can shove the cheese down the sloping path toward the exit.
Effect: The cheese acts as a boulder. It moves 40 feet in a straight line on initiative count 0.
Collision: Any creature (Poacher or Party Member) in the line must make a Standard Agility Save.
Failure: Take 8 Bludgeoning Damage and be knocked Prone.
Creative Play: Players can aim the cheese at the path the Poachers must descend to intercept them, effectively bowling them over.
The Greedy Choice (The Gold)
As the party makes their escape near the exit, they pass the corpse of Valmir's lead liaison. Beside him, half-sunken in the mud, is the Payment Chest.
The Temptation: It contains 1,000 Gold (Group Pot).
The Problem: It weighs 50 lbs. A character carrying the cheese cannot carry the chest. A character carrying the chest moves at Half Speed.
The Risk: One of the Giants has noticed the commotion near the exit and is turning. The ground shakes as he approaches.
The Check: Grabbing the chest requires a Hard (-2) Agility check to scoop it up without breaking stride.
Failure: The character fumbles. The Giant gets an Attack of Opportunity (The Club Slam).
Resolution
Once the party clears the basin rim, the Giants do not follow (they stay to guard their mammoths/fight the remaining poachers).
Loot Obtained:
The Package: The Grand Champion Cheese (Secured).
Dwarven Bow of Storms: Looted from the Poacher Captain's body (if killed) or dropped if he was bowled over.
Stats: Damage 10. Enchantment: 5 Shock Damage to Health and FP.
The Gold: 1,000 Gold (Conditional on the Greedy Choice).
Transition: "You have the vintage, the goat, and the cheese. The sun has touched the horizon. The music from the manor is drifting down the mountain. The Gala is starting."

PART 3: THE GALA DEFENSE
Location: Lakeview Manor Construction Site
 Time: Nightfall
The Scene
(Read Aloud)
"You return to Lakeview Manor as the last light of the sun bleeds out of the sky. The transformation is remarkable. The mud of the courtyard has been covered in thick rugs, torches blaze from every sconce, and the Great Hall is filled with the sound of a string quartet and the murmur of polite conversation.
Inside, through the massive glass doors, you see the guests. Jarl Siddgeir lounges on a throne, looking bored. A cadre of Thalmor Justiciars, led by the First Emissary, sip wine with expressions of disdain.
Thane Valmir rushes to meet you at the threshold. He is practically vibrating with anxiety.
'You have them? The courses? Thank the Eight! Bring them in, quickly! The Emissary is asking about the wine pairing!'"
(The Presentation)
The party presents the items. The Vintage is uncorked (the Thalmor nod approvingly). Buttercup is placed on a pedestal (it bleats and sparks, the nobles clap politely). The Grand Champion Cheese is wheeled in (the smell is pungent, earthy, and overwhelming).
The Trigger:
Just as Valmir raises a toast, a howl cuts through the music. Not the playful bleat of the goat, but the starving shriek of a predator.
The scent of the cheese—and the gathered blood of the nobility—has drawn attention from the woods.
Thalmor Ambassador: "What is that noise? Is this part of the entertainment?"
The Breach
(Read Aloud)
"From the treeline, shapes emerge. Pale, gaunt figures in tattered finery moving with unnatural speed. Death Hounds lope at their heels, frost dripping from their jaws.
Leading them is a Vampire Mistwalker, a creature of aristocracy and rot, wearing a breastplate of blood-red steel. He stares at the nobles through the glass with starving, hateful eyes.
Valmir shrieks. 'Guards! Protect the guests!'
The Thalmor Ambassador sneers. He draws a key, locks the heavy glass doors from the inside, and draws the curtains.
'Do not let the filth in. Let the help deal with it.'
The lock clicks. You are trapped in the construction yard. The vampires are charging."
GM Note: Dynamic Reinforcements
Before rolling initiative, check the party's previous actions in Objectives A and B. These are not just stat adjustments; they are scripted entrances.
1. The Laborers (From Objective A)
If the Party was Hostile: The woods are silent. The party fights alone.
If the Party was Generous (Paid/Fed them): In the middle of Round 2, a drunken roar echoes from the treeline.
The Entrance: "Tipsy" Torbjorn stumbles out of the darkness, brandishing a woodcutter's axe, followed by three laborers. They are drunk on expensive wine and adrenaline.
Dialogue: "Hey! Fancy-pants! You forgot your receipt!"
Effect: They charge the Death Hounds. They act as Minions (1 HP, low damage), but they physically block the hounds from swarming the players. The players can now focus entirely on the Boss without being flanked.
2. The Vampire Fledglings (From Objective B)
The attacking mob includes the two Cognizant Fledglings the party met in the cave. They are flanking the Mistwalker.
If the Party KILLED them previously: They are absent. However, the Mistwalker knows.


Dialogue: "I smell the ash on your clothes. You murdered my kin in the grotto! I will drink you dry for this!"
Effect: Enraged. The Mistwalker gains +4 Damage on all attacks due to bloodlust. He ignores the nobles and tunnels on the party.
If the Party SPARED them: As the mob charges, the two Fledglings get a clear look at the party in the torchlight. They stop dead in their tracks, skidding in the mud.


Dialogue: "It's them! The ones with the fire-goat! I'm not doing this again! Run!"
The Betrayal: The Fledglings turn and flee back into the woods, signaling two of the Death Hounds to follow them.
The Mistwalker's Reaction: The Boss stops his charge, looking back at his retreating minions in disbelief. He screams after them: "You dare turn your backs on the Blood? Cowards! Traitors! I will feast on your marrow when I am done here!"
Effect: The encounter size is significantly reduced (2 Vampires and 2 Hounds removed). The Mistwalker loses his flankers.
3. Buttercup the Goat
If Mistreated: The goat is panicked by the noise. If a player tries to grab or direct it, they must succeed on a Hard (-2) Animal Handling check. On a failure, Buttercup kicks them or sneezes a gout of fire at the player (4 Fire Damage).
If Treated Well: The goat sticks close to the party for safety. A player can use a Bonus Action to point the goat at an enemy. Buttercup sneezes a Cone of Fire (4 Damage) at that target.
The Combat Encounter
Terrain: The Courtyard.
Ground: The mud is Difficult Terrain, but the expensive rugs laid over it create paths of Normal Terrain. Smart players will stick to the rugs for mobility.
Lighting: The courtyard is Dimly Lit by torches. The vampires do not suffer sunlight penalties, but shadows are plentiful for stealth.
The "Construction" Hazards (Environmental Weapons):
The players are Adept, but they are outnumbered. Encourage them to use the site against the enemy.
The Suspended Stone: A pallet of cut stone blocks hangs from a pulley system above the main path.


Action: Attack the Rope (AC 10, 1 HP).
Effect: The pallet crashes down. Instant Kill on any Minion beneath it. If it hits the Boss, he takes 20 Bludgeoning Damage and is Pinned (Restrained, Strength check TN 16 to escape).
The Scaffolding: Wooden towers along the walls.


Action: Might Check (Standard) to kick the supports.
Effect: The tower collapses outward. Anyone on it falls 15 feet. Anyone in the landing zone takes 10 Bludgeoning Damage from debris.
The Quicklime: A barrel of white powder near the mixing trough.


Action: Tip it over (Interaction).
Effect: A white cloud fills a 10ft radius. Creatures inside suffer Blindness (Disadvantage on attacks) for 2 rounds due to chemical irritation.
Enemy Roster
1x Vampire Mistwalker (Boss). KEBOH ZACH AVA ME 
2x Cognizant Fledglings (The ones from the Cave - use Standard Vampire Fledgling stats if they fight).
2x Death Hounds (Minions).
(Note: If the "Cowardice" event triggers, the 2 Fledglings flee and take 2 Death Hounds with them, leaving only the Boss and 2 Hounds).
Enemy Stat Blocks
Vampire Mistwalker
Archetype: Adept Tier, Threat Level 3 Boss (Skirmisher/Caster)
Stats: Agility 16, Magic 14, Might 12, Guile 14.
HP: 70/60 (Durable due to magical armor).
DR: 7/8 (He is wearing the Vampire's Plate—heavy red steel).
Weakness: Fire (Takes x2 Damage).
Equipment: Ebony Dagger (10 Damage).
Abilities:
Vampiric Drain (Spell): Ranged attack. Deals 8 Magic Damage and heals the Mistwalker for 4 HP.
Mist Form (Reaction): When hit by a Physical attack, the vampire dissolves into mist after taking damage.
Effect: He becomes Immune to Physical Damage and can move through enemies/objects until the start of his next turn. He effectively "ghosts" away from melee combos.
Tactics: He is arrogant but tactical. He uses Mist Form to escape being surrounded. He prioritizes targets who use Fire (like the Goat or a Mage). If the Fledglings fled, he fights with a desperate, manic fury, shouting insults at the party: "You think you are hunters? You are cattle with swords!"
Death Hound
Archetype: Novice Tier, Threat Level 1 Minion (Glass Cannon)
Stats: Agility 14, Might 12.
HP: 10.
Damage: 4 (Frost Bite).
Effect: On a hit, the target is Slowed (Loses Minor Action) due to the freezing cold of the bite.
Tactics: They act as a pack. They swarm the nearest target, trying to slow them down so the Mistwalker can drain them.
Resolution
Victory Trigger: The Vampire Mistwalker dies.
(Read Aloud)
"The Mistwalker lets out a final, gurgling hiss as he crumbles. His heavy red armor clatters empty onto the muddy rugs, surrounded by a pile of ash. Seeing their master destroyed, the remaining Death Hounds yelp and scatter into the night.
Silence falls over the courtyard, broken only by the crackle of torches.
Then, from inside the Great Hall, you hear the sound of slow, polite applause.
The Thalmor Ambassador steps to the glass doors and unlocks them. He looks out at the carnage—the ash, the blood, the ruined construction equipment—with a look of mild amusement.
'Amusing,' he says, stepping over a pile of vampire ash to inspect the dead Boss's armor. 'A bit messy, certainly. But... spirited. Skyrim is so quaint.'
Thane Valmir pushes past him, rushing out into the mud. He checks his reflection in a window, frantically smoothing his velvet doublet.
'You saved it! Did you see? They loved it! They think it was a performance! A dinner theater!'"
The Rewards
Valmir is ecstatic. He wants to pay you immediately and get you off the property before you bleed on the guests.
Gold: 600 Gold per player (Handed over in heavy purses stamped with the Thalmor seal—a subtle reminder of where his funding comes from).
Item (Stripped from the Boss): Vampire's Plate.
Visual: A suit of jagged, blood-red Steel Plate armor. It is cold to the touch.
Effect: Fortify Health. The wearer gains +15 Maximum HP.
Advancement: 1 AP per player.
(Note: Ensure the players have recorded the Laborer's Amulet, Ring of the Hearth, and Dwarven Bow of Storms from earlier).
Ending:
"You stand in the cold night air, pockets heavy with gold, watching the nobles feast inside the warm hall. The string quartet begins to play again. You solved their problems, fought their monsters, and saved their lives. And they didn't even offer you a plate."
[ADVENTURE COMPLETE]

APPENDIX: DIRECTOR'S PACING GUIDE
Total Runtime: 3 Hours (180 Minutes)
0:00 – 0:20: The Hook (Lakeview Manor)
Goal: Establish tone, grab the quest, get moving.
On Rails: Do not roleplay the arrival at the gate. Start the scene mid-conversation with Thane Valmir screaming at a contractor about the drapes.
The Expository Dump: Valmir hands them a literal shopping list. Do not make them hunt for clues.
Prop Idea: Give the players the physical list (Wine, Goat, Cheese) so they don't ask "What are we doing?" later.
The Transition: "The sun is already lowering. You have to move. Which do you go for first?"
0:20 – 0:50: Objective A - The Vintage (The Warm-Up)
Goal: Quick moral dilemma or quick combat.
Travel: Skip it. "You ride hard to the ravine. You see the overturned cart."
The Encounter: The Laborers are drunk.
Pacing Tool: The Intimidation Check.
If the party tries to talk: Give them one chance to roll Guile/Intimidation.
Success: The laborers flee/trade immediately.
Failure: Initiative.
Combat Speed: The laborers are Minions (died in 1-2 hits). This fight should not last more than 15 minutes. It is a warm-up to test their Adept-tier dice.
0:50 – 1:30: Objective B - The Pyro-Goat (The Chaos)
Goal: Solve a dynamic combat puzzle.
Travel: Montage. "The woods darken as you reach the Grotto."
The Rail: Do not use a dungeon map. The cave is one room.
The Scene: Enter directly into the standoff. Vampires on one side, Goat on a rock, Party at the entrance.
Pacing Tool: The Goat Timer.
At the end of every round, the Goat bleats (Fire Cone). This forces players to act fast or get burned.
The Vampires are willing to bargain immediately. Do not force a fight to the death if the players talk. "Just take it!" is a valid resolution that saves 20 minutes.
1:30 – 2:10: Objective C - The Cheese (The Heist)
Goal: High tension stealth/skills.
Travel: Montage.
The Scene: Secunda's Kiss.
Pacing Tool: The Active Battlefield.
The Giants and Poachers are already fighting. The party does not need to kill them. They need to sneak past them.
The Skill Challenge: Do not use round-by-round movement. Use "Phases."
Phase 1: Approach the Shelf (Agility).
Phase 2: Lift the Cheese (Might).
Phase 3: The Getaway (Agility/Athletics).
Fail Forward: If they fail a stealth roll, do not roll initiative with the Giants (that takes too long). Instead, the Poachers spot them and start shooting. It becomes a chase scene.
2:10 – 2:20: The Return (The Breath)
Goal: Reset and Prep.
Travel: "You haul the goods back to the Manor as the sun touches the horizon. The music is playing. The guests are seated."
The Setup: Give them 5 minutes of real-time to look at the "Construction Site" map and place their minis/tokens. "Where do you stand when the presentation happens?"
2:20 – 2:50: The Climax (The Gala Defense)
Goal: The Big Fight.
The Trigger: Thane Valmir unveils the cheese. The Vampire Mistwalker bursts from the treeline.
Pacing Tool: Fast Enemies.
The Death Hounds move fast and hit hard (Glass Cannons).
The Boss (Mistwalker) goes for the civilians (forcing player reaction).
Environmental Kills: Encourage the use of the pulleys/scaffolds. If a player shoots a rope to drop a rock, it's an Instant Kill on a minion. Don't roll damage. This speeds up the fight and makes them feel smart.
2:50 – 3:00: Resolution
Goal: Loot and Laughs.
The Scene: Valmir is covered in blood/dust but delighted. "What a show!"
The Payoff: Hand out the gold and items immediately. End on a high note.
GM Cheat Sheet: The Rails
To keep this schedule, you must enforce the following Narrative Shortcuts:
No Shopping: The players start with their gear. There is no time to stop at a shop in Falkreath. "The shops are closed due to the crisis."
No Random Encounters: The roads are dangerous, but we don't have time to play it out. Narrate them seeing a wolf pack in the distance, but drive past.
No Looting the Chaff: Do not let them spend 10 minutes looting the pockets of the Laborers or the Poachers. "They have rusty axes and lint. You move on." Only loot the Bosses/Objective Leaders (who have the magic items).
The "Giant" Rule: Under no circumstances let them fight the Giant. If they try, the Giant kicks a Poacher into the stratosphere as a warning. "You cannot win this fight. Steal the cheese and run."

REWARDS SUMMARY (Adept Tier / 4 AP)
This distribution ensures there is a reward for every major archetype (Warrior, Mage, Thief/Archer, Support).
Gold: 600 Gold per player (Total Pot: ~2,400 - 3,000g).
Reasoning: This is a wealthy Thane paying for luxury during wartime. He pays a premium.
Item 1 (From Objective A - The Vintage): The Laborer's Amulet
Visual: A heavy iron medallion on a leather cord, worn by the Bandit Leader.
Effect: Fortify Stamina/FP. The wearer gains +10 Maximum FP.
Why: Useful for any class, but specifically helps the "Bandit" theme of endurance.
Item 2 (From Objective B - The Pyro-Goat): Ring of the Hearth
Visual: A ruby ring worn by the Cognizant Fledgling.
Effect: Resist Fire. The wearer takes Half Damage from all fire sources.
Why: Essential for fighting the goat (or dragons later).
Item 3 (From Objective C - The Cheese): Dwarven Bow of Storms
Visual: A high-tech Dwemer bow carried by the Poacher Captain.
Effect: Shock Damage. Deals standard bow damage + 5 Shock Damage (drains Magicka/FP from targets).
Why: A strong ranged upgrade for the party skirmisher.
Item 4 (From Climax - The Gala): Vampire's Plate
Visual: The stylish, blood-red Steel Plate armor worn by the Mistwalker Boss.
Effect: Fortify Health. The wearer gains +15 Maximum HP.
Why: A solid defensive upgrade for the party tank.
